<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-6-4">
        <title><m>\S 6.4</m>: Intermediate Value Theorem</title>


				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that if <m>f: \mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> is a continuous function and <m>C</m> is a connected set, then the image <m>f(C)</m> is connected.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               Suppose <m>f</m> is a real function and let <m>I=[a,b]</m> be a closed interval.
Prove that if <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>I</m> such that <m>f(a) \lt 0 \lt f(b)</m> or <m>f(b) \lt 0 \lt f(a)</m>, then there exists <m>r \in I</m> such that <m>f(r) =0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                           Suppose <m>f</m> is a real function and let <m>I=[a,b]</m> be a closed interval.
Prove that if <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>I</m> such that <m>f(a) \lt c \lt f(b)</m> or <m>f(b) \lt c \lt f(a)</m>, then there exists <m>r \in I</m> such that <m>f(r) =c</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Is the converse of the Intermediate Value Theorem true? If so, prove it. Otherwise, provide a counterexample. 
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Let <m>f:[0,1] \to \mathbb{R}</m> be a function such that <m>f(0)=-1</m>, <m>f(1)=1</m>, and <m>f([0,1])=\{-1,1\}</m>.
Prove that there exists <m>a \in [0,1]</m> such that <m>f</m> is not continuous at <m>a</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>


                    
                </exercise>

                
                
                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>